    'auto_detect_language_warning_sep_value' => '<div class="callout callout-info" style="margin-bottom: 0;">
<ul>
	<li>By selecting the "<strong>User\'s Browser Language</strong>" option, the system will detect the user\'s browser language and compare it with the first language (separated with comma, available in the country edition form) of the user\'s IP address country (if this country is activated in the system)... This will prevent to always select "en" or "en-US" as first browser language code (as that is the case with the famous browsers).
<br>If the user\'s IP address country is not activated or all its languages (separated with comma in the country edition form) are not available in the system, the detected browser first language (that is available in the system) will be selected.</li>
	<li>By selecting the "<strong>Website Country Language</strong>" option, the system will detect and select the website country first language (separated with comma, available in the country edition form) available in the system.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>NOTE:</strong> This feature is only linked to the front office. And as PHP sessions are used, you have always need to clear your browser cookies if you want to check if everything works fine (Optional). Also the "<strong>User\'s Browser Language</strong>" option cannot be used (properly) in local since your IP address (127.0.0.1 or ::1) is not linked to any country.
<br>This feature is not to be confused with the <a href="#admin#/languages">languages management</a> (adding, editing, deleting languages or setting a language as default language).</p>
</div>',
